post_text: ALERT: Google is experiencing issues with Google Drive, and mitigation work is currently underway by Google's engineering team. Affected users are able to access Google Drive, but are seeing error messages, high latency and/or other unexpected behavior. Because Schoology and Google Classroom integrate with Google Drive, they are also experiencing issues with the use of Google Drive.
text: ALERT: Google is experiencing issues with Google Drive, and mitigation work is currently underway by Google's engineering team. Affected users are able to access Google Drive, but are seeing error messages, high latency and/or other unexpected behavior. Because Schoology and Google Classroom integrate with Google Drive, they are also experiencing issues with the use of Google Drive.

We are aware of two technology-related issues that may be affecting students and teachers.

We have received reports that students are having trouble accessing Google Drive. Google is aware of the problem and is working to correct the issue.

In addition, some teachers are having trouble using Zoom from their classroom this morning. This appears to be an issue with our network and our Informational Technology department is working to fix the problem.

post_text: Due to COVID-19 and the health authorities' guidance pertaining to social distancing and other safety protocols, the ACT administration of the June 13 test has been cancelled at more than 2,600 college and high school sites across the country including five in WCS. Parents and students have begun receiving notices. WCS will continue to monitor health authority restrictions in hopes that the ACT can be administered in July. The 57 page list of closed sites for June is located here: https://www.act.org/content/dam/act/unsecured/documents/2020/Closed-Test-Centers-June.pdf. In addition, parents might find the ACT COVID-19 web page helpful in learning more: https://www.act.org/content/act/en/covid-19.html.
text: Due to COVID-19 and the health authorities' guidance pertaining to social distancing and other safety protocols, the ACT administration of the June 13 test has been cancelled at more than 2,600 college and high school sites across the country including five in WCS. Parents and students have begun receiving notices. WCS will continue to monitor health authority restrictions in hopes that the ACT can be administered in July. The 57 page list of closed sites for June is located here: https://www.act.org/content/dam/act/unsecured/documents/2020/Closed-Test-Centers-June.pdf. In addition, parents might find the ACT COVID-19 web page helpful in learning more: https://www.act.org/content/act/en/covid-19.html.

post_text: We have some important news to share for families in the southern part of the county. The Well Outreach will offer a Mobile Food Pantry Express for families in need this Saturday, March 21 at 9 a.m. at Spring Hill High School. According the The Well Outreach, families will be asked to stay in their cars, and they will receive a numbered spot. The cars will be called up by row and volunteers will load the food items directly into the trunk or back seat.

According the The Well Outreach, families will be asked to stay in their cars, and they will receive a numbered spot. The cars will be called up by row and volunteers will load the food items directly into the trunk or back seat.

post_text: ‪REMINDER: WCS Food Services and One Generation Away will be providing food to families in the Fairview area starting tomorrow. From 10 a.m. until noon Friday, volunteers will be at Westwood Elementary handing out non-perishable goods to those in need. Just drive up and it will be brought to you! On Saturday, volunteers will be at the same location from 10 a.m. until noon, and they will be handing out fresh produce.

post_text:
Our Food Services Department has been working with organizations in our county and with the Franklin Special Food Services Department to provide food for families while we are out of school.

WCS and One Generation Away will be distributing non perishable food boxes at Westwood Elementary School on Friday, March 20 from 10 a.m. until 12 p.m., on Saturday, March 21 from 10 a.m. until 12 p.m. fresh produce will be distributed. Families are asked to drive up and the food will be delivered to their car.

When plans with other agencies are finalized, we will share that information on our website at https://www.wcs.edu/food-distribution/

post_text:
URGENT: Today, Tennessee Governor Bill Lee urged all school districts to close through Tuesday, March 31, 2020, to help mitigate the spread of Coronavirus, COVID-19, in our State. However, Williamson County Schools will be closed through the remainder of that week, Friday, April 3, 2020.

The School Age Child Care program will remain closed.

We know our employees and families have many questions. We will communicate additional information with our staff later this week. Also, we will continue to communicate with families regarding any additional instructional services that may be provided during the time we are closed.

Please continue to visit the school district website for updates and additional information.

Thank you for your continued patience and support as we work together through this public health emergency.

post_text:
THIS JUST IN: As you know, last evening a parent in the Brentwood area notified the district that they had tested positive for the Coronavirus and that they had visited a school prior to that diagnosis. The Tennessee Department of Health completed its investigation today and confirmed that the parent had COVID-19. The Department implemented their protocols and those in direct contact with the parent while symptomatic have been notified.

While we work to learn more about the impact of this virus on our schools, Williamson County Schools will remain closed on Wednesday, March 11, 2020.

The School Aged Child Care program will be open at inclement weather sites following inclement weather hours for those families who need that service. Twelve month employees should follow the inclement weather protocol.

Again, no school in Williamson County on March 11, 2020.

post_text:
URGENT: Late yesterday, a parent in the Brentwood area notified the district that they had tested positive for the Coronavirus and that they had visited a school prior to that diagnosis. We are working with the Tennessee Department of Health who has notified us that they will begin investigating this report today including investigating any contact with WCS faculty, staff and students, if needed. To assist with this process, Williamson County Schools will be closed on Tuesday, March 10, 2020.

The School Aged Child Care program will be open at inclement weather sites following inclement weather hours for those families who need that service. Twelve month employees should follow the inclement weather protocol.

The district will continue working with the Tennessee Department of Health, the Williamson County Health Department and Williamson County Emergency Management through this process.

THIS JUST IN: As a result of the devastating storms that hit Middle Tennessee overnight, Nashville Mayor John Cooper has requested that all extracurricular activities be canceled today. That means the 6AAA Region Basketball Tournament will be delayed by one day.

As a result, the Brentwood High and Summit High boys teams will now play Wednesday; the Brentwood High and Page High girls teams will play in the championship game Thursday; and the boys championship game will take place Friday. All games are being held at Overton High School.

post_text: Parents and students are working together to craft a vision for the new Legacy Middle School in Franklin. The first school community activity was held earlier this month and a list of words were determined to help guide the school. Those words are community, cooperation, opportunity, visionary, creativity, integrity, friendship, potential, exciting, accepting, innovative, teamwork, bravery, preparation, challenging, inclusion, leadership, inclusivity and good vibes.

post_text: Second grade students at Winstead Elementary are celebrating their love of math this Valentine’s Day. To end their line graph lesson, students used conversation hearts to demonstrate what they learned. They counted how many candy hearts of each color were in their boxes and used that to determine how their graphs would look.
